Fill and boil your #kettle{} for the couscous. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @yellow pepper{1}(halved and thinly sliced) and @green pepper{1}(halved and thinly sliced) and discard their core and seeds. Slice them into thin strips. Roughly chop the @coriander{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Zest the @lemon{1/2}(zested and juiced). Chop the @halloumi{250%g}(chopped widthways into 3 slices per person) widthways into 3 slices per person.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} over medium heat. Once hot, add the onion and peppers to the pan. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @black pepper{pinch}, stir everything together, then cook until the peppers have softened, ~{6-8%minutes} stirring often.

In the meantime, pop the @couscous{150%g} in a #bowl{} with a good pinch of salt and pepper and the @olive oil{1%tbsp}. Pour the @boiling water{} for the couscous (see ingredients for amount) into the bowl, cover tightly with #cling film{} and leave to the side for ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve.

Once the onion and peppers have softened, stir in the garlic and @chermoula spice mix{1%tbsp}. Cook for ~{1%minute}, then pour in the @finely chopped tomatoes{1%400g can} and the @water{} for the sauce (see ingredients for amount). Add a pinch of @sugar{pinch} and season with salt and pepper. Simmer until thick and tomatoey, ~{8-10%minutes}. Stir occasionally.

> Add a splash of water to the mixture if it gets a little thick.

In the meantime, heat another frying pan over medium high heat (don't use any oil!). Lay the halloumi slices in the pan and fry until golden, ~{2-3%minutes} on each side. Once nicely coloured, remove from the heat.

When the tomato mixture has thickened, pop the halloumi on top. Cover with the #lid{} or #foil{}, cook for ~{2%minutes} more to ensure the halloumi is hot! Fluff up the couscous with a #fork{}, stir in the lemon zest and half the coriander. Season to taste with salt, pepper and a small squeeze of lemon juice. When everything is ready, share the couscous between bowls, spoon the shakshuka on top. Sprinkle over the remaining coriander. Enjoy!